Q3

Recall how logical indexing of a dataframe works in R. To refresh your memory, in the example code below I ask R for the median magnitude for quakes whose longitude is greater than 175. The two ways produce equivalent results.
median(quakes$mag[quakes$long>175])
## [1] 4.5
median(quakes[quakes$long>175,]$mag) #this is the more conventional notation
## [1] 4.5

3.1 (1 pt)

Explain what each of the two lines of code are doing in words. Specifically, why do we need to use the comma in the second case but not in the first? Remember that the $ selects a single variable and that [ ] are used for indexing whatever object came before (either a single variable or a dataframe).

Your answer goes here. 1-2 sentences only. The two lines of code are returning the median mag value for quakes that had a long value greater than 175. You need the comma in the second line of code since it is making the call for rows that are longer than 175, and the comma specifies you want all the corresponding columns to such rows (to which you then choose to focus on the mag column); You do not need a comma in the first line of code since we restrict the search to the column mag before searching through which corresponding rows have a long value greater than 175.

3.2 (3 pts)

What is the mean of the variable mag when depth is greater than the median depth? What is the mean of the variable mag when depth is less than the median depth? What does this suggest about the relationship between an earthquakes depth and its magnitude?
mean(quakes[quakes$depth > median(quakes$depth),]$mag)
## [1] 4.5232
mean(quakes[quakes$depth < median(quakes$depth),]$mag)
## [1] 4.7176
plot(quakes$depth, quakes$mag)

Your answer goes here. 1-2 sentences only. The mean mag when depth is greater than the median depth is 4.5232; The mean mag when depth is less than the median depth is 4.7176. This data indicates that quakes with a smaller depth may have a larger mag compared to a different quake with a larger depth; there is not enough data to make a claim such that there is an inverse relationship as the distribution of values would be needed: As shown by the scatterplot, there is an inverse relationship between depth and maximum magnitude up until a certain depth, but after that, there is no distinct trend. It would be an overstatement to claim an inverse relationship exists for all depths and magnitudes.

3.3 (2 pts)

What is the standard deviation of the variable lat when depth is greater than the median depth? What is the standard deviation of the variable lat when depth is less than the median depth? What does this suggest about the relationship between an earthquakes latitude and its depth?
sd(quakes[quakes$depth > median(quakes$depth),]$lat)
## [1] 3.577252
sd(quakes[quakes$depth < median(quakes$depth),]$lat)
## [1] 6.1501
plot(quakes$depth, quakes$lat)

Your answer goes here. 1-2 sentences only. The standard deviation for lat when depth is greater than the median depth is 3.577252; The standard deviation for lat when depth is less than the median depth is 6.1501. This data suggests quakes with a greater depth more consistently occur within a certain [smaller] range of lat values compared to quakes with a smaller depth which occur at a much larger range of lat values.

Q5

Lets make some plots in base R.

5.1 (2 pt)

Create a boxplot of depth using the boxplot() function. Describe where you see the min, max, and median (which you calculated in question 2) in this plot.
boxplot(quakes$depth)

Your answer goes here. 1-2 sentences only. The minimum, maximum, mean, and median values for the variable depth are 40.0, 680.0, 311.4, and 247.0 respectively. On the boxplot, the minimum value (40.0) is the lower tail of the plot, the maximum value (680.0) is the upper tail of the plot, and the median value (247.0) is the thicker line in the box.

5.2 (2 pt)

Create a histogram of depth using the hist() function. What important information does the histogram provide that the boxplot does not?
hist(quakes$depth)

Your answer goes here. 1-2 sentences only. The histogram better illustrates the distribution of values compared to a boxplot. While both can indicate whether the distributions are normal or skewed, the histogram provides a more clear view of the distribution such as the two peaks/hills of data distribution (which cannot be seen in the boxplot).

5.3 (2 pt)

Create a scatterplot by plotting variables mag and stations against each other using the plot() function. Note that to generate a scatterplot, the plot() takes two arguments: the x-axis variable and the y-axis variable. Describe the relationship between the two variables.
plot(quakes$mag, quakes$stations)

Your answer goes here. 1-2 sentences only. The scatterplot shows a positive correlation between the mag and stations: the greater the mag, there are often a greater number of stations. That said, the distribution of these values are left skewed in that there are more observations for lower mag areas with their corresponding lower number of stations.

5.4 (3 pt)

Create scatterplot of the quakes geographic locations by plotting long on the x-axis and lat on the y-axis. Using this plot, and the map/link below (note the two trenches), and some of the techniques you practiced above, are deeper quakes more likely to originate east or west of Fiji?

Link to location on Google maps

plot(quakes$long, quakes$lat)

hist(quakes[quakes$long > 175,]$depth)

hist(quakes[quakes$long < 175,]$depth)

mean(quakes[quakes$long > 175,]$depth)
## [1] 347.9182
mean(quakes[quakes$long < 175,]$depth)
## [1] 169.639

Your answer goes here. 1-2 sentences only. The mean depth for quakes in East Fiji is 347.918, while the mean depth for quakes in West Fiji is 169.639. Moreover, the histograms show a significantly higher frequency of deeper quakes in East Fiji compared to West Fiji, thus it is reasonable to conclude that deeper quakes are more likely to originate in East Fiji.
